Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, the European powers were burning up in the desire to go deep into the Turkish backland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps from the European border, is one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the travel books say.
The building encircles the end of the platforms, with a tower at each front corner, and looks like some kind of German rural town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building's a little bumpy.
However, in view of the interior of the vault ticket office, it is clear what a large enterprise this was the most western gate.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the "late future of conquests', with the help of this railway from Damascus to Baghdad, to Saudi Arabia today, wanted to achieve its ambitions to seize the Middle East.
The German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
His railroad routes were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
Relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and squeezed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
Hyderpasha Station was no better.
In 1917, a munitions train exploded and destroyed the nicely developed roof of the building.
According to Turkish sources, there was a sabotage operation.
Since then, it's been falling apart, and history has gone way beyond that.
At the same time today, as the gateway to Anatolia and the railway to the entire eastern region, at least symbolically, it serves as the expanding diplomatic horizon for Turkey.
The Justice and Development Party on the Government - the AKP - has developed a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The new policy is marked by commitment.
It is remarkable that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the groups of Hamas and Fatah in Palestine, with Iraq, with Iran, with the European Union and, of course, with the United States.
I wanted to assess the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I got on the night train to Ankara in Turkey to visit one of the leading foreign policy experts in the AKP, the Turkish Member of Parliament, Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours of tumbling, which gave me the rhythm of the famous documentary about the old world, "The Night Mail" - I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is meant to be the symbol of the new secular state, which turns its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, known to have Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
It caused some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern building of stone and steel, specifically designed for this purpose - which is located in a developing suburban district, between semi-finished shopping centres and coffee houses. The latter meets the middle managers in suits - both men and women - to make a deal early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have been introduced to a right-centre-based politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy aim is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
"The Cold War has overturned order," he said.
Turkey is isolated from its backland.
He had to turn east and west at the same time today.
He couldn't choose between the two.
He had to open both ways.
"But is it possible that sooner or later you will be forced to choose?" I asked.
"Turkey never wanted to go on a crossroads."
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here was mechanically repeating: Turkey's relations with not only the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the countries around the Black Sea are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as it is to Turkey itself.
It is as if they want to convey the message that, in metaphorically speaking, all of Europe, along with Turkey, can reach Asia and the Middle East on those railway lines heading east.
When I was back at Hydarpasha Station, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, the two German gentlemen who watched the recovery of this fine construction 100 years ago.
How would they have been surprised to know that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East are now largely in Turkey's hands.
And as I was waiting at the port for the ferry to take me back through the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was once called "the sick man of Europe."
At the time, at least there was no question of which continent would claim this exciting country.
