The non-collision "bee car"
For the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has inspired its new invention from nature, precisely from the world of bees.
The Japanese company designed a robot to avoid accidents by mimicking the flying of bees.
The Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C may be the first step in developing anti-collision technologies.
Engineers of the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center have built this small robot in Japan in cooperation with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Centre of the famous University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Technology PRand Research Development Mark Director, the BR23C is a further extension of the four-level safety barrier of Nissan.
The robot makes the company's product more complete to avoid impact.
When flying, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety barrier.
However, there is a more important role to play in the complex eye of the uterus, with which it can see at an angle of more than 300 degrees in each direction. Consequently, it can fly in its own personal space.
To copy the function of the composite eye, engineers designed a so-called laser remote meter (Laser Range Finder).
The apparatus identifies obstacles in a 180-degree field of vision before the BR23C, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an operation to avoid impact.
"As soon as the barrier is detected, the small robot, imitating the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid impact.
The main thing that distinguishes the system from the instruments currently available is that in this case the evasive manoeuvre takes place completely automatically.
If not, the robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles, "explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of Mobility Laboratory and Chief Engineer of the project.
In a way other than bees, the evasive manoeuvre shall not be directed upwards or downwards, nor shall it move diagonally, in only two dimensions and only towards the invertification of the wheels, i.e. not in an infinite direction and in a way, as in the case of bees.
In addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used a rotation function in the robot to avoid collisions.
"This structure only needs to process and respond to data every few seconds.
There is no need to store data or intuitive logic based on previous manoeuvres, so it can operate without interruption with just a few dozen KB memories.
This may sound surprising, but it's not gigabyte, but we're not even talking about megabyte-sized memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology that Nissan estimates can enter serial-made cars within 10 years.
The robot operates with lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and durable than lithium-ion.
In the future, the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system may be an additional way of using it to deliver the car to its destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
