The terms announced on Monday also show that the agreement has been amended in recent days: last Monday Morgan announced that 20% of its shares would be sold to the Japanese company for approximately $8.5 billion.
"A week ago, we thought that the share would be wholly made up of ordinary shares," said Toshihide Mizuno, CEO of MUFG in Tokyo.
"However, due to the current market and economic situation, we wanted to minimise and prevent potential risks."
With regard to the weighted average price, MUFG pays 7% more than the book value for Morgan Stanley shares.
As a result of the transaction, the return per share is reduced by around 20%.
Under the agreement, MUFG may transfer half of its preference shares to ordinary shares after one year if the trading price of the latter exceeds the conversion rate by more than 50% over a specified period, i.e. it rises to around 47 dollars.
Morgan Stanley thus ensures that funds from the MUFG can make use of its investment opportunities, improve its balance sheet and increase its liquid resources.
However, the spokesperson of the group did not wish to provide accurate information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG's entry, Morgan Stanley is expected to increase Tier I's solvency rate by about 15%, which will be one of the best in its own sector.
Morgan has declared that its balance sheet has "definitely" improved since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been a great ordeal for the group, as the stock price has fallen to half, while the cost of providing it against the risk of default has skyrocketed.
This cost was reduced on Monday, but it remained high at around 12%.
The only remaining "survivor" of the large investment banks remained after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch. This is Goldman Sachs, which announced last week that it had received $15 billion: part of this came from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett's group.
Rafael Correa's Monday statement, Quito
Rebuilding the Republic in the spirit of 21st century socialism.
This is the joint plan for Hugo Chávez, Evo Morales, Venezuela, and Rafael Correa, Ecuador.
Following the model of his fellow presidents and friends, Correa presented his ideas about the new constitution on Sunday.
He succeeded in his mission, as 64% of the voters voted in favour of the referendum according to official results, which covered 80% of the votes.
According to this, 28% of the population voted no, 7% of the votes were invalid, while 0.7% were unfilled by voters.
The adoption of the draft Constitution required 50% + 1 vote.
On Sunday, both the surveys at the exit of the polling offices and the counting by a civilian organisation have demonstrated the enormous superiority of the votes' yes' with a rate of 63% and 70% respectively.
By the way, Rafael Correa was already talking about the victory of his draft constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution was an overwhelming victory," he said, and thanked the Ecuador at the headquarters of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As is well known, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez, Morales and the Chilean presidents, Michelle Bachelet.
According to the report of the OAS observation mission, the vote took place in a calm atmosphere. Its main theme was a 444-point text, which summed up the principles of "new socialism" protected by the President.
The proposed Constitution places state power in the service of the economy, while maintaining the right of the State to design "development 'for a country that essentially lives from oil extraction by foreign companies and foreign currency sent by emigrants.
The draft Constitution of Correa, which was elected in 2006, also strengthens the power of the head of state, who can obtain a mandate for a maximum of two consecutive periods and is entitled to the dissolution of the Parliament.
Correa has already announced that she wishes to take advantage of this opportunity and will re-compete for the Head of State mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also included the freedom of health services and education. The President has already started to introduce this in his country, which has 13.9 million inhabitants and half of the population is living below the minimum.
Finally, the Constitution prohibits the presence of foreign troops in the country, which could put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of the US anti-drugs facility in Ecuador.
They freed the 19 hostages in Chad.
Egyptian commando raided the kidnappers who took 11 tourists and eight of their escorts hostage ten days ago.
The hostages are now in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and eight Egyptian escorts were held in the desert for 10 days, from which they were transported unharmed to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
The hostages were released in Chad by an Egyptian commando this morning.
In good condition, apparently, they arrived at the Al-Maza military base around 4: 30 p.m., directly linked to the international airport in Cairo.
The hostages were forbidden to comment to the press, and immediately moved to a hospital in the suburbs of Cairo in Maadi, where they were examined.
The hostages are "healthy" and "no ransom was paid to the kidnappers," said the Egyptian tourist minister Zoheir Garanna at the airport.
On September 19, the hostages were taken prisoner at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border areas of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, where they were involved in an SUV safari, and the group was then carried from one shelter to another by the 35 unknown hostages.
In the group there were 11 tourists (five Italian men, five German men and one Romanian woman), and eight Egyptians: two tour guides, four drivers, one border guard and director of the Aegyptous travel agency organising safari.
According to an Egyptian head of security, a special commando of 30 arrived on two helicopters on the scene, where they raided the hostages immediately before dawn.
Half the kidnappers were killed, the others fled, "said the leader asking for his name to be silenced.
He also said that a total of 150 special forces were sent from the Egyptian Lightning Brigade to Sudan, where German and Italian commandos were added.
The Italian diplomatic leader Franco Frattini, who is currently in Belgrade, stressed the role of secret agents and special Italian action groups.
"We have to admit that this result could not have been achieved without the professional and effective intervention of our secret service men and action groups," he said, without further details.
He also denied payment of ransom for the hostages.
On the day before, the Sudanese army announced that an SUV was detained while patrolling, on which the kidnappers traveled, six of them were killed (including the Chad leader) and two were arrested.
According to the military, the hostages were involved with a rebel organization in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which was immediately betrayed by the organization concerned.
