They nationalize part of Fortis Bank by Benelux governments
With partial nationalisation, the Benelux States are helping the US credit market crisis, as a first European, in the Belgian-Dutch bank, Fortis: the three countries support the financial and insurance institution with an interest in Hungary with a total of EUR 11,2 billion.
The Belgian, Luxembourg and the Dutch governments discussed the matter at the highest level at the end of the week, involving the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission in charge of competition.
In the euro area, Fortis Bank has the first major crisis in the waves in the context of an international financial market crisis that has been around for over a year, and decisions on the bank can therefore, in some respects, be regarded as precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states will purchase the bank's existing assets in close half (49%).
The bank will certainly sell some of its interests, including, above all, activities purchased from ABN Amro, the Netherlands last year, mainly insurance companies.
Fortis's stock started a steep fall last week, and in the second half of the week, there were serious crisis phenomena at the institute.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with an employee of 85 thousand, is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The company's papers only fell by about 12% on Friday, to 14-year-old depths.
Since January, the value of the shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
In view of the current share prices, the total market capital of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the company managers, this is not realistic.
