Fox in a henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to enter into insurance contracts with the applicant based on people's drug purchase data.
Data protection professionals fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection programme that binds the use of prescription data to the consent of the person concerned in all cases.
This should be in independent hands, otherwise we leave the foxes to the foxes, "quoting Richard Dick, the developer of the program for the follow-up of prescription drugs, Washington Post.
Insurance companies shall make the insurance premiums and the amount due in the event of damage dependent on the health status of the applicant client and shall not take insurance if they consider the risk to be too high.
In the past, the person was sent for medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the light of the results of the investigation.
Dick has invented a much cheaper procedure for ten years: he can easily obtain from pharmacies, based on the customer's identification number, the drugs he's been buying for the past year and a half, and the program itself concludes what kind of illness he's suffering from and what his medical condition is.
For example, if you regularly take a high dose of cholesterol suppressant, it suggests that your blood fat level is virtually unmanageable, which immediately classifies it as a higher risk.
There are several versions of the programme on the market, some of them also set a risk factor, so the insurance company will have little work to do outside the paperwork, although small difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include that some medicines may be used for several purposes, such as against migraines or heat waves, but are also effective against depression.
The latter is considered to be a significant risk-raising factor for business insurers, not the latter.
They formed separate companies to retrieve and process the data, and they, before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies, ask the patient for consent.
They are now bound by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their failure to do so.
Some companies are already processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to drug consumption data, so they can provide a more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to the data, and the monitoring of the use at the same time will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate health data protection law, but it covers only healthcare providers and insurance companies.
Before Congress, there is a bill that gives the authorities control over companies specialising in the provision of data.
Dick Richard understands that this is not enough: that is why he has further developed his programme, which would tie the data to the explicit consent of the data subject.
Another question is that the person concerned may hardly refuse to contribute, otherwise the insurance companies will not enter into a contract with him.
So the hens are somewhat dependent on the kindness of the fox.
