They found the plane of the billionaire, Steve Fossett, who disappeared a year ago.
They found the remains of the billionaire Steve Fossett's plane, who disappeared on September 3, 2007 above the Nevada desert.
The wreckage was found on a 3,000-metre-tall plateau in the Sierra Nevada Mountains on the border of California and Nevada, near Mammoth Lakes.
No human remains were found inside the plane.
John Anderson, the sheriff of Madera County, cleared up all the doubts that still existed: "After determining the position of the plane, we sent out a team, and now we can be sure it's the plane Steve Fossett was flying on the day of his disappearance," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff also confirmed that there were no human remains found in the plane or surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The US Transport Safety Agency (NTSB) stated that a committee of inquiry was requested a few hours after the wreck was discovered, which was able to identify the machine and that it was indeed the Bellanca 8kcab that disappeared on 3 September 2007, on the day Fossett left for a three-hour flight from Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, too, in California, near the Nevada border, a couple found some of Fossett's personal belongings near his home in Mammoth Lakes.
Two I.D.s for Fosset, issued by the Illinois FAA, some cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was dispatched a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire set up several peaks to put himself in history.
